ity of aesthetic and sociopolitical contexts in which these affective dependencies become central to these authors' representations of selfhood. By setting these novels and poems in conversation with the work of contemporary theorists, she illuminates pressing and unanswered questions about subjectivity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAffect (Psychology) in literature. 0aDomestic space in literature. 0aLiterature, Moderny20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aModernism (Literature). 0aSubjectivity in literature. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPhilosophy & Religion. 4aPhilosophy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh  amodernist novels, literary criticism, literary analysis, subjective interdependence, distributed cognition.1 aAshbery, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaldwin, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEllison, Ralph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFitzgerald, F. Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPlath, Sylvia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aProust, Marcel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStevens, Wallace, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWoolf, Virginia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501714245?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501714245423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501714245/original  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_